node.text:
This is the tale of two livers! 
Both of these livers are from dead people. Both of these livers were donated after death, but only one of them was able to be used for a life saving liver transplant! Can you guess which one? 
The top liver is from a patient who died a cardiac related death. When the transplant surgeon opened up this patient he noticed that this liver was enlarged with fatty infiltrate and congestion and decided this liver was not healthy enough to transplant in someone. Compare this liver to the one in the bottom photo which is a nice size and color and looks healthy. A liver transplant is needed in cases where a patient has end stage liver disease and their liver is no longer functioning. If a person needs a liver transplant sometimes they are fortunate enough to get a donation from a friend or family member. In other cases they must receive a liver donation from a person who died. 
Sometimes people ask me if they can be organ donors because of various health conditions. I suggest everyone list themselves as organ donors. Let the surgeon decide if your organs are healthy enough to be transplanted in someone.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Nicole Angemi, MS, PA (ASCP) on August 23, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Mystery Diagnosis Harlequin ichthyosis!'.

node.text:
Our skin is our largest organ! The skin is the first barrier we have to protect our bodies from trauma and infection. It also is responsible for regulating our body temperature and controlling water loss. 
Harlequin ichthyosis is a very rare genetic disorder of the skin where babies are born looking like this, with very hard, thick skin covering most of their bodies. The thickened skin does not function normally. It is not flexible and causes restricted movement. This can be life threatening because it can restrict breathing. The thickened skin also can crack with movement increasing the risk for infection. In the past these babies only lived for a few weeks, but now with improved treatments and medical support patients with harlequin ichthyosis can now live into adolescence and adulthood. This condition has features that can be recognized by a high resolution ultrasound during pregnancy and can be confirmed with a fetal skin biopsy or amniocentesis.

node.text:
A staghorn calculus is a giant branching kidney stone! When you see a kidney stone this big it means it did not come out easy, either it was surgically removed or that the person is dead! The kidney stone has this appearance because it has formed in the renal pelvis (where the urine collects in the kidney after it is made). These stones can be formed for multiple reasons. Sometimes certain bacteria that can cause urinary tract infections release substances that mix with the substances in urine. This chemical reaction can create the formation of these large stones. If these stones are not removed they can create an obstruction which can lead to an infection in the kidney, sepsis, and ultimately death. 
For more pathology cases like this check out The Gross Room! Now only $20 for a whole year of GROSS! 🔪
